observations.recommendation:
For the Local Chief Executive to:
a.) Constitute a Disposal Committee which shall be composed of, but not limited to, an
official with a rank or function not lower than a Department Head I as the
Chairperson, head of the administrative service/division or equivalent, and head of
the Property Section or GSO;
b.) Send correspondence or make representation to donor agency to inquire regarding
the ownership of the donated PPE items.
For the Disposal Committee:
c.) Inspect the properties for disposal if accurate as described in the Inventory and
Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) or equivalent document,
appraise and undertake the valuation of the unserviceable PPE;
d.) Determine and recommend the appropriate mode of disposal;
e.) Undertake the disposal proceedings of the property;
f.) If the property is to be disposed of as junk, verify parts that could be salvaged or
profitably used for another property or serve as spare part, in consultation with
persons with technical expertise;
For the General Services Officer (GSO)/Property Unit:
g.) Prepare and submit to the Disposal Committee the IIRUP, Waste Material Report
(WMR), and or Property Transfer Report (PTR) as appropriate;
h.) Replace the damaged/illegible property tag with a sticker/tag that could withstand
exposure to the elements;
i.) Properly monitor the renewal of motor vehicle registration to avoid future penalties;
j.) Insure all insurable properties to indemnify or compensate for any damage to, or loss
of all its properties in case of destruction;
For the Municipal Accountant:
k.) Upon disposal of properties and receipt of the updated IIRUP, derecognize/ drop from
the books all disposed properties and provide necessary disclosure in the Notes to
Financial Statements (FS);
l.) For the donated properties recorded in the books of the LGU, with no deed of donation
or equivalent document, and are found to be still owned by the source agency, provide
necessary adjusting entries and proper disclosure in the Notes to FS.

Upon the completion of the physical count of the Inventory Committee, the Local Chief Executive institutes measures to properly dispose of all obsolete and unserviceable properties pursuant to the directives of Section 79 of PD 144 and Section 379-381 of RA 7160 and in accordance with the procedures cited in COA Circular 89-296;

11.1. Immediately review the accounting records to determine the assets eligible for dropping and reconcile them with the records of the property custodian;
11.2. Continuously reconcile the result of the physical count with the property and accounting records; and Determine the recoverable amount from the obsolete and unserviceable assets and recognize appropriate impairment loss;
11.3. Adjust the books of accounts and the property records, as warranted, after the reconciliation; and Reverse the entry made by the management in the derecognition of PPE accounts and follow the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006.

Require the Municipal Accountant to recognize all completed Road Network Assets on cost or fair value whichever is applicable and provide the appropriate depreciation for the depreciable component of the road network following the straight-line method without provision for residual value;

Require the Municipal Accountant to recompute the accumulated depreciation of the completed Road Network Assets and to prepare Journal Entry Voucher recognizing correction or adjustments for the understatement thereof; and

Further, to direct the Municipal Accountant, the MGSO, and the Municipal Engineer and the Inventory Committee to strictly perform their duties and responsibilities in the accounting and reporting of Local Road Network as mandated under COA Circular No. 2015-008 and submit to the Auditor not later than January 31 of the ensuing year the required inventory reports duly reconciled with the Accounting records particularly the Report on Local Road Network (RLRN) and Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network (RPCLRN)

For the Local Chief Executive to require the offices/officials concerned to identify the gaps in the determination and implementation of development projects, thereby coming up with corrective measures to ensure optimal utilization of funds and timely delivery of value-added services and benefits to constituents;

For the Local Development Council and Local Finance Committee to assign specific timelines for the identified development projects to evaluate achievement rate and identify areas with a significant shortfall or needs improvement to make timely and periodic remedial measures and determine the feasibility of implementation of prior year’s unimplemented projects;

For the Municipal Accountant to ensure completed Development Infrastructure Projects were fully insured against possible structural failures/defects by requiring contractors to post warranty security in the form and amounts prescribed in the Revised IRR of RA 9184 before processing the final payments.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant recognize all completed Road Network Assets on cost or fair value whichever is applicable and provide the appropriate depreciation for the depreciable component of the road network following the straight line method without provision for residual value;
Require the Municipal Accountant to recompute the accumulated depreciation of the completed Road Network Assets and to prepare Journal Entry Voucher recognizing correction or adjustments for the understatement thereof; and
Further for the Management to direct the Municipal Accountant, the MGSO, and the Municipal Engineer and the Inventory Committee to strictly perform their duties and responsibilities in the accounting and reporting of Local Road Network as mandated under COA Circular No. 2015-008 and submit to the Auditor not later than January 31 of the ensuing year the required inventory reports duly reconciled with the Accounting records particularly the Report on Local Road Network (RLRN) and Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network (RPCLRN).

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to instruct the concerned official personnel to:
Require the BAC Secretariat to review carefully the contents of PPMPs and APP and ensure that all procurement of the agency is in accordance with the approved PPMPs and APP;
Implement strictly timelines on the posting and submission of procurement reports;
Establish procurement timelines in consonance with project schedules, including a cut-off date for processing requisitions and issuance of purchase orders to ensure receipt of most of the procured items in time for the project implementation;
Strict observance of RA 9184 and its IRR, and other existing rules and regulations on government procurement is enjoined as well as imposition of control measures to ensure that procurement is effected in an efficient, economical and effective manner that is most advantageous to the government and to prevent possible disallowances for such violation.

We recommend that the local chief executive to:

Require the Municipal Accountant to update and submit immediately the bank reconciliation statements for the months of September to December 31, 2014 and to prepare thereon regularly the monthly bank reconciliation statements by making use of other alternative methods, in the case of the unavailability of bank statements, e.g. securing bank statements via LBP e-access or having bank snapshots as reference;

Require the Accountant to exhaust efforts in the reconciliation of the unreconciled beginning balance e.g. application of work-back process;

Require the Accountant to review the unrecorded long outstanding reconciling items, gather pertinent documents and draw JEVs to adjust them in the books of accounts, when necessary; and

Immediately effect the adjustment/s in the books of accounts the various errors committed in recording of some disbursements and reconcile the discrepancies noted per subsidiary ledger against statement of cash flows and other reports e.g. cash book.

We recommend that the local chief executive to;

Resort to NFA as primary supplier or source of rice in all its procurements whenever it grants rice as a form of incentive or benefit to their employees or use rice in connection with their functions; and

Forge with the NFA an appropriate Memorandum of Agreement to facilitate and operationalize the rice procurement arrangement.

We recommend that the local chief executive to:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to compute the correct amount of withholding tax vis-à-vis the basic salary and the submitted BIR Form Nos. 1902 and 2305 as evidence of the tax exemptions; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to remit to the BIR the unremitted taxes from CY 2014 together with the penalties thereof being borne by erring personnel;

Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the adjustments, if there any, based on the updated BIR forms requiring disclosures of other incomes and additional exemptions;

Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer, to verify and account for, if there any, the withholding taxes not withheld and not remitted for CY 2014.
